[1] Malaysia
Date: Sun 25 Jan 2009
Source: The Earthtimes online News [edited]
<http://www.earthtimes.org/articles/show/252315,malaysian-sees-sharp-increase-in-dengue-fever-cases.html>


Of Malaysia's 13 states, 3 recorded a sharp increase in the number of
cases and deaths caused by the mosquito-borne dengue fever [virus]
this year [2009], news reports said Sunday [25 Jan 2009]. Central
Selangor state, with the highest number of cases, combined with the
northern states of Penang and Kedah to make up 71 percent of the
total 4221 cases, and 12 fatalities have been recorded nationwide
since 1 Jan [2009], the Star daily reported.

The figures were almost triple the 1514 cases and 4 deaths recorded
in the same period last year [2008].

"I hope everyone will cooperate with us to get the situation under
control," said Health Minister Liow Tiong Lai.

On Monday [19 Jan 2009], Malaysia's health ministry raised a health
alert following the increase in dengue cases, calling local councils
and the public to work together.

The symptoms of dengue, [the virus of] which is carried by the
_Aedes_ mosquito, include high fever, rashes, headaches, and muscle
and joint pain. If not detected and treated early, the disease can be
fatal.

The government has been holding campaigns to educate the public as
well as conduct checks for mosquito-breeding sites on residential and
construction sites to try to stem dengue cases.

Despite the efforts, the number of cases and deaths continues to rise
each year.

--
