[3] Australia (Blood donation, Queensland)
Date: Fri 23 Jan 2009
Source: Brisbane Times [edited]
<http://www.brisbanetimes.com.au/news/queensland/blood-crisis-grows-as-dengue-sucks-supplies/2009/01/23/1232471579955.html>


The Red Cross has issued an urgent call for blood donors because the
dengue fever outbreak in north Queensland has robbed them of 14
percent of their regular supply.

The Australian Red Cross Blood Service (ARCBS) Queensland medical
services manager Dr Matt Lee-Archer said the service asked donors who
had recently recovered from dengue or who had traveled to
dengue-affected areas to wait another 4 weeks before donating whole
blood.

At the moment, this includes Cairns and Townsville, which between
them contribute one in 7 Queensland donors.

ARCBS expects the safety measure will cause a shortage of donors for
at least the next 4 months.

Three north Queensland blood donor centres are now affected by the
dengue fever outbreaks, ARCBS Queensland Operations Manager Anthony
Bourke said last week.

"Without the support of other Queensland regions, this has the
potential to be devastating to our future stock levels, and support
from the remainder of the state is required for the next 4 months,"
he said.

Dr Lee-Archer encouraged those affected by restrictions to continue
to give platelets, which are involved in the clotting of blood, and
resume whole bloods after 4 weeks.

"People in the affected areas can still give platelets, and it's
really important that they do," he said.

The donated platelets are used to restore platelet levels in those
undergoing chemotherapy and only have a shelf-life of 5 days.

The restrictions were put in place when a dengue outbreak occurred
Cairns on 1 Dec of last year [2008] and Townsville in early January
this year [2009].

Dr Lee-Archer said dengue fever could be transmitted via blood
transfusions, and the current restrictions were introduced because no
large scale screening test for the virus is licensed for Australia.

"That's why its important that more people know about the (blood
supply) shortage and donate," he said.

An ARCBS spokeswoman said the restrictions would be lifted 4 months
after the last recorded case in the dengue outbreak but noted that
more cases were expected in the current outbreak.

[Byline: Andrew Wight]

--
Communicated by
ProMED-mail Rapporteur A-Lan Banks

[This is an interesting but troublesome example of health problems
caused indirectly by a dengue virus outbreak. - Mod.TY]

******
[4] Fiji
Date: Fri 23 Jan 2009
Source: Fiji Live [edited]
<http://www.fijilive.com/news_new/index.php/news/show_news/12978>


Close to 43 dengue cases have been reported in the Northern Division
following the recent flash floods, the new interim Health Minister,
Dr Neil Sharma, confirmed.

Dr Sharma told Fijilive that the majority of the cases have been
reported in the Macuata and Cakaudrove provinces.

"We are advising people nationwide to boil all sources of drinking
water and to get rid of containers that have stored water, as it is a
mosquito breeding zone," he said.

Dr Sharma said people should also protect themselves from mosquito bites.

"There has been no major outbreak reported in the Western Division;
however, we are concerned about water contamination," he said.

--
