[5] Bolivia
Date: Tue 20 Jan 2009
Source: Aguas digital.com [Spanish, trans. & summ. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www.aguasdigital.com/actualidad/leer.php?idnota=1855712&efenew=1>


Bolivian health authorities have detected a dengue outbreak in an
area near the border with Argentina and today [20 Jan 2009] revealed
the death of a 3rd DHF victim this week [week of 18 Jan 2009].

The classical dengue outbreak was detected in the area of Yacuiba on
the border with Argentina in the southern department [state or
province equivalent - Mod.TY] of Tarija, and it is suspected that it
could affect around 200 people, according to the television chain ATB.

Bolivia has found itself in a "health emergency" due to the dengue
epidemic, the disease [virus] being transmitted by the _Aedes
aegypti_ mosquito, which is abundant in tropical areas and is
especially reproductively active during the rainy season.

DHF today [20 Jan 2009] took the life of its 3rd victim of the week
in Bolivia with the death of a child of 11 years, reported Alfredo
Rodriguez, chief of intensive therapy of the Hospital del Nino
[Children's Hospital] in La Paz.

"Unfortunately, we could not save him. He arrived in a comatose state
with a hemorrhagic syndrome, bleeding from his skin, intestines and
stomach," the physician said.

Just in the Sant Cruz region, there are now 1350 suspected cases
according to the Director of Epidemiology of the department, Roberto
Torrez.

The other main [dengue] outbreaks are in the areas of central
Cochabamba, the tropical zones of La Paz [department], and in the
city of Riberalta, in the Beni region (northeast Bolivia).

--
