[6] Brazil (Minas Gerais)
Date: Thu 22 Jan 2009
Source: Uai [Portuguese, trans. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www.uai.com.br/UAI/html/sessao_2/2009/01/22/em_noticia_interna,id_sessao=2&id_noticia=96289/em_noticia_interna.shtml>


Juiz de Fora is on alert to combat the dengue [virus vector]
mosquito. The city government announced Wednesday [21 Jan 2009] the
results of a study done 5-12 [Jan 2009] that showed that 2.75 percent
of the buildings surveyed had larvae of the mosquito [_Aedes
aegypti_]. In October 2008 the figure was 0.63 percent.

According to the Municipal Health Secretariat, in 2008, only 417
[dengue] cases were registered in the city [including one death from
DHF].

For the World Health Organization (WHO), any rate [of _Ae. aegypti_
household infestation] that is above one percent is considered
alarming. Among the 191 districts of the city, 83 have [dengue]
outbreaks. The situation is worse in the north and east. In some of
these locations, the [household index] exceeded 7 percent. The WHO
considers that there is epidemic risk where the household index is
over 4 percent.

The mayor, Custodio Mattos, reported that the necessary actions are
being taken jointly involving all spheres of public authority to
resolve the [mosquito vector] problem. "The rate of infestation is
extremely high in some places and very high in the city as a whole.
The risk of an epidemic is very great, and we have to unite to combat
dengue," he said.

Custodio said that an effort will be made between all the municipal
secretariats so that in a month, 80 000 buildings in the city will be
surveyed. As the Department of Health does not have sufficient staff
to go to all the sites, survey staff from other agencies will help to
accomplish the work. Besides them, the fire department is pledged to
help with visits. It is proposed to raise a contingent of 500 people.

The mayor called for the involvement of the population. "We are
facing a difficult enemy to fight. If people do not help by reporting
and participating, our work could have 1000 people and yet not go
ahead," he said.

--
